# lit-review

`lit-review` is a local pipeline for building an evidence-backed feature set
from academic literature. The full path is:

```text
draft.md / seed PDFs
  -> LitHarvest paper collection
  -> LitSynth PDF conversion and chunk index
  -> LitExtract feature extraction
  -> LLM curation
  -> final feature inventory
  -> comparison and sanity-check plots
```

The repository is intentionally API-first. It does not scrape Google Scholar,
bypass paywalls, solve CAPTCHAs, or automate browser sessions. LitHarvest uses
open scholarly metadata APIs and downloads only PDFs that are openly accessible
or directly exposed in returned metadata.

## 1. Set Up

Install the project environment:

```bash
uv sync
```

The package exposes these commands:

```bash
uv run lit-harvest --help
uv run lit-synthesize --help
uv run lit-extract --help
uv run lit-log-summary --help
uv run comparison-plots --help
uv run feature-embedding-tsne --help
```

For live harvests and LLM-backed extraction, set the credentials you need:

```bash
export LITHARVEST_EMAIL="you@example.com"
export UNPAYWALL_EMAIL="you@example.com"
export SEMANTIC_SCHOLAR_API_KEY="optional-semantic-scholar-key"
export GEMINI_API_KEY="your-gemini-key"
export OPENAI_API_KEY="your-openai-compatible-key"
```

The SemEval sanity configs use `GEMINI_API_KEY` through `api_key_env`. LitSynth
and LitExtract also accept OpenAI-compatible keys through `OPENAI_API_KEY`,
`LIT_SYNTH_OPENAI_API_KEY`, or `LIT_EXTRACT_OPENAI_API_KEY`.

## 2. Define The Target Feature Set

Use two Markdown files to keep the collection and extraction focused:

- `draft.md`: search target for LitHarvest. This should describe the research
  area, candidate labels, search phrases, and inclusion priorities.
- `goal.md`: extraction and curation target. This should define the feature
  families you want in the final taxonomy.

For this repository, the current target is a persuasion/media attribute
taxonomy with three major categories:

- persuasion techniques
- moral framing
- sentiment or affective targeting

Edit these files before starting a new feature-set run. The more explicit the
target labels and exclusion criteria are, the less cleanup the curation stages
need later.

## 3. Harvest Candidate Papers

Start with the checked-in SemEval sanity config, or copy it as a template for a
new run:

```bash
uv run lit-harvest --config harvest_configs/config.semeval_2020_task11_sanity.json --dry-run
```

The dry run previews draft parsing and generated queries without API calls or
downloads. When the query set looks right, run the harvest:

```bash
uv run lit-harvest --config harvest_configs/config.semeval_2020_task11_sanity.json
```

The example config writes to:

```text
collected_semeval_2020_task11_papers/
  *.pdf
  logs/
    manifest.json
    download_log.json
    candidates.json
    candidates.csv
    candidates.bib
```

`manifest.json` is the main run record. It contains the effective config,
extracted terms, generated queries, every candidate, dedupe evidence, PDF
resolution attempts, and download status. `download_log.json` is the resumable
download ledger.

If a harvest is interrupted, rerun the same command. LitHarvest reuses
`logs/candidates.json` and skips completed downloads. Use these flags when you
need to change that behavior:

```bash
uv run lit-harvest --config harvest_configs/config.semeval_2020_task11_sanity.json --refresh-candidates
uv run lit-harvest --config harvest_configs/config.semeval_2020_task11_sanity.json --retry-failed-downloads
```

To summarize which services produced candidates and PDFs:

```bash
uv run lit-log-summary collected_semeval_2020_task11_papers/logs \
  --output collected_semeval_2020_task11_papers/logs/service_summary.json
```

Useful harvest controls:

- `max_queries`, `top_k_per_query`, and `max_downloads` control run size.
- `sources` can include `openalex`, `semantic_scholar`, `crossref`, and
  `europe_pmc`.
- `year_from` and `year_to` constrain publication years.
- `unpaywall_email` enables DOI-based open-access PDF resolution.
- `web_search_sources` can enable `brave` or `serpapi` fallback search when
  API metadata does not expose PDF URLs.
- `allow_abstract_fallback` controls whether abstract-only PDFs can be created.

## 4. Optional: Harvest From Seed PDF Citations

Use citation mode when you already have core PDFs and want one-hop collection
from their reference lists. Citation extraction uses an LLM, then LitHarvest
resolves the cited works through scholarly metadata APIs.

```bash
uv run lit-harvest \
  --harvest-mode citations \
  --core-pdf ./core_papers/paper1.pdf \
  --core-pdf-dir ./more_core_papers \
  --citation-extractor direct_pdf \
  --llm-provider gemini \
  --output ./citation_collected_papers \
  --email you@example.com \
  --unpaywall-email you@example.com
```

Supported citation extractors:

- `direct_pdf`: send each core PDF directly to the LLM.
- `pymupdf_markdown`: extract text locally with PyMuPDF, then send text to the
  LLM.

Citation artifacts are written under `logs/citation_extractions/`.

## 5. Convert PDFs To A LitSynth Run

LitExtract works from a LitSynth run folder. First convert harvested PDFs to
text Markdown:

```bash
uv run lit-synthesize --config synth_configs/00_convert_semeval_2020_task11_sanity.json
```

The example config reads:

```text
papers:   collected_semeval_2020_task11_papers
manifest: collected_semeval_2020_task11_papers/logs/manifest.json
out:      review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity
```

Expected conversion artifacts:

```text
review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/
  papers_md/*.md
  paper_index.json
```

`uv sync` installs `pypdf` and `PyMuPDF`, so `extractor: auto` should work for
most PDFs. If Poppler is installed, LitSynth can also use `pdftotext`.

## 6. Build And Inspect The Chunk Index

Build the SQLite FTS/BM25 index:

```bash
uv run lit-synthesize --config synth_configs/01_index_semeval_2020_task11_sanity.json
```

Expected index artifacts:

```text
review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/
  index.sqlite
  chunks.jsonl
  index_meta.json
```

Before extraction, spot-check retrieval against the goal:

```bash
uv run lit-synthesize search \
  --run review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity \
  --query "propaganda technique taxonomy loaded language name calling" \
  --limit 5
```

If the retrieved chunks are obviously off-topic, fix the harvest target or
collection before spending LLM budget on extraction.

## 7. Optional: Write A Review Report

This is not required to produce the feature set, but it is useful for reviewing
the corpus.

```bash
uv run lit-synthesize write \
  --run review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity \
  --goal goal.md \
  --output review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/report.md
```

Without an API key, LitSynth writes an offline extractive evidence report. With
an OpenAI-compatible key, it writes a narrative synthesis with retrieved chunk
citations.

You can also run convert, index, and write in one command for future runs:

```bash
uv run lit-synthesize run \
  --papers collected_semeval_2020_task11_papers \
  --manifest collected_semeval_2020_task11_papers/logs/manifest.json \
  --goal goal.md \
  --out review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity \
  --report review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/report.md
```

## 8. Preview Feature Extraction

The first LitExtract pass scans the LitSynth corpus and produces raw feature
mentions, paper-level features, and corpus-level features.

Preview the workload without LLM calls:

```bash
uv run lit-extract --config extract_configs/00_extract_semeval_2020_task11_pdf.json --dry-run
```

The example config uses direct PDF mode:

```json
{
  "command": "run",
  "run": "review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity",
  "output_dir": "review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf",
  "goal": "goal.md",
  "api_key_env": "GEMINI_API_KEY",
  "api_provider": "gemini",
  "input_mode": "pdf"
}
```

Use `input_mode: "pdf"` when your model accepts PDFs and the original PDF paths
are available in `paper_index.json`. Use `input_mode: "chunks"` for
OpenAI-compatible text-only extraction from `chunks.jsonl`.

Helpful controls:

- `paper_limit`: small smoke tests before scanning the full corpus.
- `batch_chunks`: number of text chunks per request in chunk mode.
- `max_features_per_chunk` and `max_features_per_pdf`: extraction breadth.
- `max_chunk_chars`: prompt size control in chunk mode.
- `force`: overwrite existing extraction outputs.

## 9. Run Raw Feature Extraction

Run the first pass:

```bash
uv run lit-extract --config extract_configs/00_extract_semeval_2020_task11_pdf.json
```

Expected first-pass artifacts:

```text
review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf/
  feature_mentions.jsonl
  feature_mentions.csv
  paper_features.jsonl
  paper_features.csv
  features.jsonl
  features.csv
  completed_papers.jsonl
  extraction_errors.jsonl
  extraction_trace.json
```

Use `features.csv` for a quick spreadsheet review. Use `features.jsonl` as the
machine-readable input to curation.

## 10. Curate And Consolidate Features

Curation merges duplicates, normalizes canonical names, records member
mappings, and rejects off-goal or non-taxonomic rows.

Preview the curation batches:

```bash
uv run lit-extract --config extract_configs/01_curate_semeval_2020_task11_pdf.json --dry-run
```

Run curation:

```bash
uv run lit-extract --config extract_configs/01_curate_semeval_2020_task11_pdf.json
```

Expected curation artifacts:

```text
review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf/
  curated_features.jsonl
  curated_features.csv
  curated_feature_members.jsonl
  curated_feature_members.csv
  rejected_features.jsonl
  rejected_features.csv
  final_curated_features_top100_by_category.jsonl
  final_curated_features_top100_by_category.csv
  curation_trace.json
```

`merge_style` controls synonym merging:

- `conservative`: merge only obvious duplicates.
- `moderate`: default balance for near-synonyms.
- `aggressive`: broader merges, useful when the raw extraction is noisy.

## 11. Finalize The Feature Set

The finalization pass sends ranked curated candidates by category to the LLM and
asks for a publication-ready top feature set.

Preview finalization:

```bash
uv run lit-extract --config extract_configs/02_finalize_semeval_2020_task11_pdf.json --dry-run
```

Run finalization:

```bash
uv run lit-extract --config extract_configs/02_finalize_semeval_2020_task11_pdf.json
```

The final feature inventory is:

```text
review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf/
  final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.jsonl
  final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.csv
```

Supporting finalization artifacts:

```text
final_curated_feature_members_llm.jsonl
final_curated_feature_members_llm.csv
final_rejected_features_llm.jsonl
final_rejected_features_llm.csv
final_curation_decisions.jsonl
final_curation_trace.json
```

Use the JSONL final file for downstream scripts that expect structured feature
rows. Use the CSV final file for manual review or spreadsheet handoff.

## 12. Sanity-Check Against The SemEval Inventory

The SemEval sanity check compares final extracted features with the expected
Task 11 propaganda-technique labels in
`sanity_checks/semeval_2020_task11/expected_features.csv`.

Run the default comparison:

```bash
uv run python sanity_checks/semeval_2020_task11/compare_expected_features.py
```

Compare a specific final artifact:

```bash
uv run python sanity_checks/semeval_2020_task11/compare_expected_features.py \
  --features review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf/final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.csv \
  --show-unmatched
```

Fail a CI-style run if coverage is too low:

```bash
uv run python sanity_checks/semeval_2020_task11/compare_expected_features.py \
  --features review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf/final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.csv \
  --fail-under 10
```

Generate the SemEval coverage figures:

```bash
uv run python sanity_checks/semeval_2020_task11/plot_expected_features.py \
  --extract-dir review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf \
  --output-dir review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf/figures
```

These figures summarize stage coverage, expected-label support in the final
output, category mix, and unmatched final features.

## 13. Compare Two Feature Sets

Use `comparison-plots` to compare two LitExtract-style JSON or JSONL feature
exports. The script does not read CSV input; use the `.jsonl` final artifacts.

```bash
uv run comparison-plots \
  review_runs/run_a/feature_extract_pdf/final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.jsonl \
  review_runs/run_b/feature_extract_pdf/final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.jsonl \
  --name-1 "Run A" \
  --name-2 "Run B" \
  --top-a 1 \
  --top-b 100 \
  --top-k 100 \
  --output-dir review_runs/comparisons/run_a_vs_run_b \
  --prefix run_a_vs_run_b
```

Main outputs:

```text
review_runs/comparisons/run_a_vs_run_b/
  run_a_vs_run_b_jaccard_top_1_100.png
  run_a_vs_run_b_venn_top_100.png
  run_a_vs_run_b_scatter_top_100.png
  run_a_vs_run_b_features.json
  run_a_vs_run_b_unique_top10.md
  run_a_vs_run_b_final_features.json
  run_a_vs_run_b_final_features.csv
```

By default, `top-k` is applied per category, which keeps persuasion, moral
framing, and sentiment/affect from being dominated by the largest category.

Useful options:

- `--match-scope category`: match by category plus normalized feature name.
- `--match-scope name`: match by normalized feature name only.
- `--match-normalization singular`: merge simple plural variants.
- `--venn-k` and `--scatter-k`: override the default `--top-k` for those plots.
- `--scatter-scale log`: compare feature support on a log scale.
- `--annotate-top N`: label high-count scatter points.
- `--no-category-plots`: write only overall plots.
- `--final-category-k CATEGORY=K`: manually choose final export size for one
  category.

For optional semantic matching with Gemini:

```bash
uv run comparison-plots \
  review_runs/run_a/feature_extract_pdf/final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.jsonl \
  review_runs/run_b/feature_extract_pdf/final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.jsonl \
  --name-1 "Run A" \
  --name-2 "Run B" \
  --semantic-match gemini \
  --gemini-api-key "$GEMINI_API_KEY" \
  --output-dir review_runs/comparisons/run_a_vs_run_b_semantic \
  --prefix run_a_vs_run_b_semantic
```

The semantic run writes accepted matches to
`<output-dir>/<prefix>_semantic_matches.json` before generating the plots.

## 14. Plot Feature Embeddings With tSNE

Use `feature-embedding-tsne` to embed a finalized feature set with Gemini and
visualize the result with tSNE. The command accepts CSV, JSONL, or JSON feature
exports, including the finalized LitExtract artifacts:

```text
review_runs/<run_name>/feature_extract_pdf/final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.jsonl
```

Run a plot with a reusable embedding cache:

```bash
uv run feature-embedding-tsne \
  review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf/final_curated_features_llm_top100_by_category.jsonl \
  --output-dir review_runs/semeval_2020_task11_sanity/feature_extract_pdf/figures \
  --html
```

The command writes:

```text
<prefix>_gemini_embedding_cache.jsonl
<prefix>_gemini_embedding_tsne.csv
<prefix>_gemini_embedding_tsne.png
<prefix>_gemini_embedding_tsne.html
```

By default, embedding text is built from `feature_name`, `category`,
`definitions`, and `synonyms`. Override that with `--text-fields` if your export
uses different columns.

## Testing

Run the test suite:

```bash
uv run python -m unittest discover
```

Run syntax checks for the main scripts:

```bash
uv run python -m py_compile \
  lit_harvest.py \
  lit_synthesize.py \
  lit_extract.py \
  comparison_plots.py \
  lit_log_summary.py
```

Run a no-network harvest smoke test:

```bash
uv run lit-harvest \
  --draft draft.md \
  --output /tmp/litharvest_smoke \
  --dry-run
```

## Troubleshooting

If few PDFs download, inspect `logs/manifest.json`. Many scholarly APIs return
metadata without direct PDFs, and some open-access records expose only HTML
landing pages.

If a run is too broad, reduce `max_queries`, `top_k_per_query`, or
`max_downloads`; add year filters; or narrow `draft.md`.

If a run is too narrow, add explicit `extra_queries`, include all metadata
sources, and make the draft include title-like phrases, known seed papers,
candidate labels, acronyms, and repeated technical terms.

If extraction produces generic ML features, tighten `goal.md` and reduce the
model's room to infer off-goal categories. The extraction prompt already asks
the model to ignore generic machine-learning features unless they are directly
used as persuasion, moral framing, or affect labels.

If curation over-merges labels, rerun `lit-extract curate` or `finalize` with
`merge_style: "conservative"`. If it leaves too many near-duplicates, try
`merge_style: "aggressive"`.
